<paragraph blockId="22.[163,780,1436,1703]" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">
<emphasis box="[163,327,1436,1457]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Distribution:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Cumberlidge &amp; Daniels, 2022" authorityName="Cumberlidge &amp; Daniels" authorityYear="2022" box="[342,495,1436,1458]" class="Malacostraca" family="Potamonautidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="TRIBE NOV." tribe="Erimetopini">Erimetopini</taxonomicName>
is found in West and Central Africa in the following countries: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rathbun" authorityYear="1894" box="[646,779,1467,1488]" class="Malacostraca" family="Potamonautidae" genus="Erimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[646,779,1467,1488]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Erimetopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in the 
<collectingCountry box="[335,610,1497,1519]" name="Republic of the Congo" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Republic of the Congo</collectingCountry>
and the D.R. 
<collectingCountry box="[163,234,1528,1549]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Congo</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[248,328,1528,1550]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="18.[163,241,1295,1317]" captionTargetBox="[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-252@18.[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 9. Maps showing the distributional ranges of the four genera of Erimetopini (A) Erimetopus, (B) Longipotamonautes, (C) Nesonautes and (D) Occidensonautes." pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bott" baseAuthorityYear="1955" box="[349,573,1528,1549]" class="Malacostraca" family="Potamonautidae" genus="Longipotamonautes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[349,573,1528,1549]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Longipotamonautes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[687,775,1528,1550]" name="Nigeria" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[163,293,1559,1580]" name="Cameroon" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, the D.R. 
<collectingCountry box="[428,508,1559,1580]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Congo</collectingCountry>
, the 
<collectingCountry name="Central African Republic" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Central African Republic</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[279,355,1589,1611]" name="Gabon" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Gabon</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[460,718,1589,1611]" name="Republic of the Congo" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Republic of the Congo</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="18.[163,241,1295,1317]" captionTargetBox="[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-252@18.[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 9. Maps showing the distributional ranges of the four genera of Erimetopini (A) Erimetopus, (B) Longipotamonautes, (C) Nesonautes and (D) Occidensonautes." pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cumberlidge &amp; Daniels" authorityYear="2022" box="[218,351,1620,1641]" class="Malacostraca" family="Potamonautidae" genus="Nesonautes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[218,351,1620,1641]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Nesonautes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[523,718,1620,1642]" name="Sao Tome Island" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">São Tomé Island</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="18.[163,241,1295,1317]" captionTargetBox="[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-252@18.[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 9. Maps showing the distributional ranges of the four genera of Erimetopini (A) Erimetopus, (B) Longipotamonautes, (C) Nesonautes and (D) Occidensonautes." pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cumberlidge &amp; Daniels" authorityYear="2022" box="[260,449,1650,1671]" class="Malacostraca" family="Potamonautidae" genus="Occidensonautes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[260,449,1650,1671]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Occidensonautes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in West Africa from 
<collectingCountry box="[163,253,1681,1703]" name="Senegal" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Senegal</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[288,374,1681,1703]" name="Nigeria" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[389,472,1681,1703]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="18.[163,241,1295,1317]" captionTargetBox="[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-252@18.[243,1363,195,1255]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 9. Maps showing the distributional ranges of the four genera of Erimetopini (A) Erimetopus, (B) Longipotamonautes, (C) Nesonautes and (D) Occidensonautes." pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Fig. 9D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[163,780,1744,1888]" lastBlockId="22.[827,1443,197,280]" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">
<emphasis box="[163,274,1744,1765]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Remarks:</emphasis>
Each of the four genera in this tribe has been recovered as a well-supported lineage in the clade for 
<taxonomicName authority="Cumberlidge &amp; Daniels, 2022" authorityName="Cumberlidge &amp; Daniels" authorityYear="2022" box="[202,340,1805,1827]" class="Malacostraca" family="Potamonautidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="TRIBE NOV." tribe="Erimetopini">Erimetopini</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[355,435,1805,1827]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[163,244,905,927]" captionTargetBox="[164,1447,197,865]" captionTargetId="figure-453@2.[163,1449,195,866]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. A, maximum clade credibility tree of the Afrotropical freshwater crab fauna based on four DNA loci with support values (posterior probabilities and bootstrap values of the ML analyses) with a geological timescale below the tree topology. Posterior probabilities&gt; 0.95 pP (*above branch) and bootstrap values&gt; 75% (* below branch) were regarded as statistically supported and are shown on the tree topology. Clade A, Liberonautinae, clade B, Potamonautinae, clade B1, Maritimonautini, clade B2, Erimetopini, clade B3, Potamonautini. B, detail of the maximum clade credibility tree of the Afrotropical freshwater crab fauna showing Clade B3 Potamonautini with the species included in the five genera within the tribe: Arcopotamonautes (B3[1]), Lirrangopotamonautes (B3[2]), Platythelphusa (B3[3]), Potamonautes s.s. (B3[4]) and Rotundopotamonautes (B3[5])." pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
2) and these relationships are also supported by other recent molecular studies of these taxa (
<bibRefCitation author="Daniels SR &amp; Klaus S" box="[299,561,1866,1888]" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" pagination="119 - 128" refId="ref33119" refString="Daniels SR, Klaus S. 2018. Divergent evolutionary origins and biogeographic histories of two freshwater crabs (Brachyura: Potamonautes) on the West African conveyer belt islands of Sao Tome and Principe. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 127: 119 - 128." type="journal article" year="2018">Daniels &amp; Klaus, 2018</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wood LE &amp; De Grave S &amp; Cumberlidge N &amp; Kennerley A &amp; Daniels SR" box="[645,884,197,1888]" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290" pagination="2219 - 2230" refId="ref37030" refString="Wood LE, De Grave S, Cumberlidge N, Kennerley A, Daniels SR. 2019. A phylogenetic perspective on biodiversity patterns of Afrotropical freshwater crabs (Crustacea, Decapoda, Potamonautidae). Aquatic Conservation: Marine and Freshwater Ecosystems 29: 2219 - 2230." type="journal article" year="2019">
Wood 
<emphasis box="[715,773,1866,1888]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">et al.</emphasis>
, 2019
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1). The genera can be distinguished from each other by differences in the G1 TA (
<figureCitation box="[1282,1393,228,250]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="14.[163,241,1342,1364]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1303]" captionTargetId="figure-309@14.[163,1443,195,1303]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 4. Gonopods 1 and 2 of the four genera in Erimetopini. A–C, Erimetopus vandenbrandeni; D–F, Longipotamonautes ballayi; G–I, Nesonautes margaritarius; J–L, Occidensonautes ecorssei. Scale bar: A–L = 2.0 mm." pageId="22" pageNumber="1290">Fig. 4A–L</figureCitation>
; see key to genera above).
</paragraph>
